Yes. The clean way to get best of both worlds is:

one cold artifact graph + two hot minds

core model

Keep Beast2 itself deterministic and local:
	•	.c core
	•	non-blocking UI
	•	reserve 512MB for UI
	•	sqlite as core primitive
	•	local LLM execution only

Then split LLM usage into two modes:

1. fresh llm

Small, rebuilt context each call.

Use for:
	•	parsing a request
	•	generating options
	•	reviewing a result
	•	escaping drift
	•	summarizing old work

Strength:
	•	low drift
	•	predictable
	•	fast reset

Weakness:
	•	weak continuity

2. old llm

Longer-lived task session with accumulated transforms.

Use for:
	•	active local task execution
	•	iterative design/code refinement
	•	maintaining short-term intent
	•	working a single factory lane

Strength:
	•	continuity
	•	momentum
	•	better local task adaptation

Weakness:
	•	drift
	•	hidden assumptions
	•	context bloat

best-of-both-worlds architecture

Do not let either mode own truth.

Truth lives in SQLite artifacts.

user intent
→ fresh llm parses task
→ emits factory spec
→ old llm executes transforms inside bounded task session
→ results written as artifacts/logs/sqlite rows
→ fresh llm periodically audits/summarizes/resets lane

So:

fresh = planner / auditor
old = worker / improver
sqlite = truth

sqlite primitives

Use a tiny set of tables:

artifacts
transforms
sessions
messages
tasks
hot_context_refs
ratings

Minimum useful idea:
	•	artifacts: immutable outputs, specs, code snapshots, summaries
	•	transforms: parent → child edges
	•	sessions: old-llm working lanes
	•	messages: prompt/response records if worth keeping
	•	tasks: bounded goals
	•	hot_context_refs: which artifacts are loaded into current old-llm window

This gives you:

append-only memory
+ queryable history
+ resumable task lanes

factory approach for local task optimization

For something like Match Made in Hell, define a factory lane per task.

Example:

factory: mmih-dialog-scene-ui
goal: improve dialogue scene editor
inputs: current code + issue + target behavior
stop: patch or debug artifact exists
budget: 20 min / N tokens / M transforms

Flow:

fresh llm

Builds the factory spec:
	•	what subsystem
	•	what files
	•	what stop condition
	•	what evaluation criteria
	•	what artifact types to emit

old llm

Stays inside that lane only:
	•	reads selected code artifacts
	•	proposes patch/debug/design note
	•	emits transform artifacts
	•	never expands scope on its own

fresh llm again

Every few transforms:
	•	compresses session
	•	checks drift
	•	decides continue / fork / stop
	•	rebuilds the next hot context from SQLite

That gives you continuity without trusting a bloated old session forever.

hot context selection

This is the key part.

For each task lane, build hot context from:
	•	current task spec
	•	current target files
	•	last accepted patch
	•	last accepted summary
	•	relevant failures
	•	3 to 10 strongest linked artifacts

Not full history.

Use SQLite queries to assemble this.

cold log = everything
hot context = selected subset

That matches your ring-buffer idea.

non-blocking UI with 512MB reserved

Treat the LLM system as background workers only.

Rules:
	•	UI thread never waits on LLM
	•	every LLM job is cancellable
	•	partial outputs stream into SQLite/logs
	•	UI reads job state from DB/events
	•	hard memory ceiling for inference workers so UI reserve is protected

Good split:

ui reserve: fixed 512MB
llm workers: capped pool
db thread: lightweight
artifact indexing: background low priority

For local models, it may help to run only one heavy inference lane at a time unless the machine clearly has headroom.

old llm session rules

Old llm should not be immortal.

Give it boundaries:
	•	max transforms per session
	•	max token budget
	•	max age
	•	periodic fresh audit
	•	forced summary checkpoints
	•	resumable by artifact, not by raw transcript only

That means "old" is really:

task-conditioned continuity
not endless memory

artifact types worth standardizing

For Beast2, a few artifact types will go far:
	•	spec
	•	summary
	•	patch
	•	debug_guess
	•	file_selection
	•	evaluation
	•	decision
	•	session_checkpoint

Then every transform can be something like:

spec -> file_selection -> patch -> evaluation -> decision

example: Match Made in Hell

Say you want to improve a conversation scene system.

Fresh llm:
	•	parses request
	•	identifies relevant files
	•	emits mmih-scene-dialogue-factory.spec

Old llm:
	•	reads current scene code
	•	proposes patch for branching node editor
	•	emits patch artifact
	•	emits debug notes if patch weak

SQLite:
	•	records patch, parent files, task lane, evaluation

Fresh llm:
	•	reviews patch against goal
	•	says accept / reject / fork
	•	rebuilds next context

This is much better than one giant agent run with all context jammed in.

why this fits Beast2

It matches your existing instincts:
	•	append-only truth
	•	artifact graph
	•	reproducibility
	•	local execution
	•	non-blocking UI
	•	small primitives
	•	generators/factories as reusable lanes

It also avoids the biggest failure mode:

old llm becomes god

It is never god. It is just a worker attached to a lane.

simplest implementation order
	1.	SQLite artifact graph first.
	2.	Fresh planner that emits factory specs.
	3.	Old worker session bound to one task.
	4.	Hot-context builder from SQLite.
	5.	Fresh auditor/resetter.
	6.	UI for viewing task lanes, artifacts, accepted outputs.

one-sentence summary

Build Beast2 so the fresh LLM plans and audits, the old LLM works inside a bounded factory lane, and SQLite artifacts--not either model state--hold the real memory.

